oking organisms, filamentous green algae, grow repeated cell division within chain cells.[13] also single-celled fungi (yeasts) form hyphae, some fungi hyphal yeast forms.[22] common some plant animal species, 70 fungal species display bioluminescence.[23] unique features: some species grow unicellular yeasts reproduce budding binary fission. dimorphic fungi switch yeast phase hyphal phase response environmental conditions.[22] fungal cell wall composed glucans chitin; glucans also found plants chitin exoskeleton arthropods,[24][25] fungi organisms combine two structural molecules cell wall. unlike plants oomycetes, fungal cell walls contain cellulose.[26] omphalotus nidiformis, bioluminescent mushroom fungi lack efficient system long-distance transport water nutrients, xylem phloem many plants. overcome limitation, some fungi, armillaria, form rhizomorphs,[27] resemble perform functions similar roots plants. eukaryotes, fungi possess biosynthetic pathway producing terpenes uses mevalonic acid pyrophosphate chemical building blocks.[28] plants some other organisms additional terpene biosynthesis pathway chloroplasts, structure fungi animals have.[29] fungi produce several secondary metabolites similar identical structure made plants.[28] many plant fungal enzymes make compounds differ other sequence other characteristics, indicates separate origins convergent evolution enzymes fungi plants.[28][30] diversity bracket fungi tree stump fungi worldwide distribution, grow wide range habitats, including extreme environments deserts areas high salt concentrations[31] ionizing radiation,[32] well deep sea sediments.[33] some survive intense uv cosmic radiation encountered space travel.[34] grow terrestrial environments, though several species live partly solely aquatic habitats, chytrid fungus batrachochytrium dendrobatidis, parasite responsible worldwide decline amphibian populations. organism spends part life cycle motile zoospore, enabling propel water enter amphibian host.[35] other examples aquatic fungi include living hydrothermal areas ocean.[36] around 100,000 species fungi formally described taxonomists,[37] global biodiversity fungus kingdom fully understood.[38] basis observations ratio number fungal species number plant species selected environments, fungal kingdom estimated contain 1.5 million species.[39] recent (2011) estimate suggests may 5 million species.[40] mycology, species historically distinguished variety methods concepts. classification based morphological characteristics, size shape spores fruiting structures, traditionally dominated fungal taxonomy.[41] species may also distinguished biochemical physiological characteristics, ability metabolize certain biochemicals, reaction chemical tests. biological species concept discriminates species based ability mate. application molecular tools, dna sequencing phylogenetic analysis, study diversity greatly enhanced resolution added robustness estimates genetic diversity within various taxonomic groups.[42] two types edible fungi mycology mycology branch biology concerned systematic study fungi, including genetic biochemical properties, taxonomy, use humans source medicine, food, psychotropic substances consumed religious purposes, well dangers, poisoning infection. field phytopathology, study plant diseases, closely related many plant pathogens fungi.[43] 1729, pier a. micheli first published descriptions fungi. use fungi humans dates back prehistory; Ötzi iceman, well-preserved mummy 5,300-year-old neolithic man found frozen austrian alps, carried two species polypore mushrooms may used tinder (fomes fomentarius), medicinal purposes (piptoporus betulinus).[44] ancient peoples used fungi food sources–often unknowingly–for millennia, preparation leavened bread fermented juices. some oldest written records contain references destruction crops probably caused pathogenic fungi.[45] history mycology relatively new science became systematic development microscope 17th century. although fungal spores first observed giambattista della porta 1588, seminal work development mycology considered publication pier antonio micheli's 1729 work nova plantarum genera.[46] micheli observed spores also showed that, proper conditions, could induced growing species fungi originated.[47] extending use binomial system nomenclature introduced carl linnaeus species plantarum (1753), dutch christian hendrik persoon (1761–1836) established first classification mushrooms skill considered founder modern mycology. later, elias magnus fries (1794–1878) elaborated classification fungi, using spore color various microscopic characteristics, methods still used taxonomists today. other notable early contributors mycology 17th–19th early 20th centuries include miles joseph berkeley, august carl joseph corda, anton de bary, brothers louis rené charles tulasne, arthur h. r. buller, curtis g. lloyd, pier andrea saccardo. 20th century seen modernization mycology come advances biochemistry, genetics, molecular biology, biotechnology. use dna sequencing technologies phylogenetic analysis provided new insights fungal relationships biodiversity, challenged traditional morphology-based groupings fungal taxonomy.[48] morphology microscopic structures environmental isolate penicillium hypha conidiophore phialide conidia septa fungi grow hyphae, cylindrical, thread-like structures 2–10µm diameter several centimeters length. hyphae grow tips (apices); new hyphae typically formed emergence new tips along existing hyphae process called branching, occasionally growing hyphal tips fork, giving rise two parallel-growing hyphae.[49] hyphae also sometimes fuse come contact, process called hyphal fusion (or anastamosis). growth processes lead development mycelium, interconnected network hyphae.[22] hyphae either septate coenocytic. septate hyphae divided compartments separated cross walls (internal cell walls, called septa, formed right angles cell wall giving hypha shape), compartment containing one nuclei; coenocytic hyphae compartmentalized.[50] septa pores allow cytoplasm, organelles, sometimes nuclei pass through; example dolipore septum fungi phylum basidiomycota.[51] coenocytic hyphae essence multinucleate supercells.[52] many species developed specialized hyphal structures nutrient uptake living hosts; examples include haustoria plant-parasitic species fungal phyla, arbuscules several mycorrhizal fungi, penetrate host cells consume nutrients.[53] although fungi opisthokonts—a grouping evolutionarily related organisms broadly characterized single posterior flagellum—all phyla except chytrids lost posterior flagella.[54] fungi unusual among eukaryotes cell wall that, addition glucans (e.g., β-1,3-glucan) other typical components, also contains biopolymer chitin.[55] macroscopic structures armillaria solidipes fungal mycelia become visible naked eye, example, various surfaces substrates, damp walls spoiled food, commonly called molds. mycelia grown solid agar media laboratory petri dishes usually referred colonies. colonies exhibit growth shapes colors (due spores pigmentation) used diagnostic features identification species groups.[56] some individual fungal colonies reach extraordinary dimensions ages case clonal colony armillaria solidipes, extends area 900ha (3.5 square miles), estimated age nearly 9,000years.[57] apothecium—a specialized structure important sexual reproduction ascomycetes—is cup-shaped fruit body often macroscopic holds hymenium, layer tissue containing spore-bearing cells.[58] fruit bodies basidiomycetes (basidiocarps) some ascomycetes sometimes grow large, many well known mushrooms. growth physiology mold growth covering decaying peach. frames taken approximately 12 hours apart period six days. growth fungi hyphae solid substrates single cells aquatic environments adapted efficient extraction nutrients, growth forms high surface area volume ratios.[59] hyphae specifically adapted growth solid surfaces, invade substrat