her scientists working fungal taxonomy.[42] recognizes seven phyla, two which—the ascomycota basidiomycota—are contained within branch representing subkingdom dikarya, species rich familiar group, including mushrooms, food-spoilage molds, plant pathogenic fungi, beer, wine, bread yeasts. accompanying cladogram depicts major fungal taxa relationship opisthokont unikont organisms, based work philippe silar[125] "the mycota: comprehensive treatise fungi experimental systems basic applied research".[126] lengths branches proportional evolutionary distances. holomycota cristidiscoidea opisthosporidia aphelida cryptomycota microsporidia metchnikovellea microsporea eumycota chytridiomycota neocallimastigomycetes chytridiomycetes hyaloraphidiomycetes monoblepharidomycetes blastocladiomycota blastocladiomycetes olpidiales entomophthoromycota basidiobolomycetes neozygitomycetes entomophthoromycetes kickxellomycota zoopagomycetes kickxellomycetes mucoromycota mortierellomycetes mucoromycetes symbiomycota glomeromycota glomeromycetes dikarya entorrhizomycota entorrhizomycetes basidiomycota ascomycota basidiomycota pucciniomycotina tritirachiomycetes mixiomycetes agaricostilbomycetes cystobasidiomycetes classiculaceae microbotryomycetes cryptomycocolacomycetes atractiellomycetes pucciniomycetes orthomycotina ustilaginomycotina monilielliomycetes malasseziomycetes ustilaginomycetes exobasidiomycetes agaricomycotina wallemiomycetes bartheletiomycetes tremellomycetes dacrymycetes agaricomycetes ascomycota taphrinomycotina neolectomycetes taphrinomycetes schizosaccharomyceta archaeorhizomycetes pneumocystidomycetes schizosaccharomycetes saccharomyceta saccharomycotina saccharomycetes pezizomycotina ?thelocarpales ?vezdaeales ?lahmiales ?triblidiales orbiliomycetes pezizomycetes leotiomyceta sordariomyceta xylonomycetes geoglossomycetes leotiomycetes laboulbeniomycetes sordariomycetes dothideomyceta coniocybomycetes lichinomycetes eurotiomycetes lecanoromycetes collemopsidiales arthoniomycetes dothideomycetes taxonomic groups see also: list fungal orders major phyla (sometimes called divisions) fungi classified mainly basis characteristics sexual reproductive structures. currently, seven phyla proposed: microsporidia, chytridiomycota, blastocladiomycota, neocallimastigomycota, glomeromycota, ascomycota, basidiomycota.[42] arbuscular mycorrhiza seen microscope. flax root cortical cells containing paired arbuscules. phylogenetic analysis demonstrated microsporidia, unicellular parasites animals protists, fairly recent highly derived endobiotic fungi (living within tissue another species).[102][127] one 2006 study concludes microsporidia sister group true fungi; is, other's closest evolutionary relative.[128] hibbett colleagues suggest analysis clash classification fungi, although microsporidia elevated phylum status, acknowledged analysis required clarify evolutionary relationships within group.[42] chytridiomycota commonly known chytrids. fungi distributed worldwide. chytrids close relatives neocallimastigomycota blastocladiomycota (below) fungi active motility, producing zoospores capable active movement aqueous phases single flagellum, leading early taxonomists classify protists. molecular phylogenies, inferred rrna sequences ribosomes, suggest chytrids basal group divergent other fungal phyla, consisting four major clades suggestive evidence paraphyly possibly polyphyly.[129] blastocladiomycota previously considered taxonomic clade within chytridiomycota. recent molecular data ultrastructural characteristics, however, place blastocladiomycota sister clade zygomycota, glomeromycota, dikarya (ascomycota basidiomycota). blastocladiomycetes saprotrophs, feeding decomposing organic matter, parasites eukaryotic groups. unlike close relatives, chytrids, exhibit zygotic meiosis, blastocladiomycetes undergo sporic meiosis.[102] neocallimastigomycota earlier placed phylum chytridomycota. members small phylum anaerobic organisms, living digestive system larger herbivorous mammals other terrestrial aquatic environments enriched cellulose (e.g., domestic waste landfill sites).[130] lack mitochondria contain hydrogenosomes mitochondrial origin. related chrytrids, neocallimastigomycetes form zoospores posteriorly uniflagellate polyflagellate.[42] members glomeromycota form arbuscular mycorrhizae, form mutualist symbiosis wherein fungal hyphae invade plant root cells species benefit resulting increased supply nutrients. known glomeromycota species reproduce asexually.[79] symbiotic association glomeromycota plants ancient, evidence dating 400 million years ago.[131] formerly part zygomycota (commonly known 'sugar' 'pin' molds), glomeromycota elevated phylum status 2001 replace older phylum zygomycota.[132] fungi placed zygomycota reassigned glomeromycota, subphyla incertae sedis mucoromycotina, kickxellomycotina, zoopagomycotina entomophthoromycotina.[42] some well-known examples fungi formerly zygomycota include black bread mold (rhizopus stolonifer), pilobolus species, capable ejecting spores several meters air.[133] medically relevant genera include mucor, rhizomucor, rhizopus. diagram apothecium (the typical cup-like reproductive structure ascomycetes) showing sterile tissues well developing mature asci. ascomycota, commonly known sac fungi ascomycetes, constitute largest taxonomic group within eumycota.[41] fungi form meiotic spores called ascospores, enclosed special sac-like structure called ascus. phylum includes morels, mushrooms truffles, unicellular yeasts (e.g., genera saccharomyces, kluyveromyces, pichia, candida), many filamentous fungi living saprotrophs, parasites, mutualistic symbionts (e.g. lichens). prominent important genera filamentous ascomycetes include aspergillus, penicillium, fusarium, claviceps. many ascomycete species observed undergoing asexual reproduction (called anamorphic species), analysis molecular data often able identify closest teleomorphs ascomycota.[134] products meiosis retained within sac-like ascus, ascomycetes used elucidating principles genetics heredity (e.g., neurospora crassa).[135] members basidiomycota, commonly known club fungi basidiomycetes, produce meiospores called basidiospores club-like stalks called basidia. common mushrooms belong group, well rust smut fungi, major pathogens grains. other important basidiomycetes include maize pathogen ustilago maydis,[136] human commensal species genus malassezia,[137] opportunistic human pathogen, cryptococcus neoformans.[138] fungus-like organisms similarities morphology lifestyle, slime molds (mycetozoans, plasmodiophorids, acrasids, fonticula labyrinthulids, amoebozoa, rhizaria, excavata, opisthokonta stramenopiles, respectively), water molds (oomycetes) hyphochytrids (both stramenopiles) formerly classified kingdom fungi, groups like mastigomycotina, gymnomycota phycomycetes. slime molds studied also protozoans, leading ambiregnal, duplicated taxonomy. unlike true fungi, cell walls oomycetes contain cellulose lack chitin. hyphochytrids chitin cellulose. slime molds lack cell wall assimilative phase (except labyrinthulids, wall scales), ingest nutrients ingestion (phagocytosis, except labyrinthulids) rather absorption (osmotrophy, fungi, labyrinthulids, oomycetes hyphochytrids). neither water molds slime molds closely related true fungi, and, therefore, taxonomists longer group kingdom fungi. nonetheless, studies oomycetes myxomycetes still often included mycology textbooks primary research literature.[139] eccrinales amoebidiales opisthokont protists, previously thought zygomycete fungi. other groups opisthokonta (e.g., corallochytrium, ichthyosporea) also given time classified fungi. genus blastocystis, stramenopiles, originally classified yeast. ellobiopsis, alveolata, considered chytrid. bacteria also included fungi some classifications, group schizomycetes. rozellida clade, including "ex-chytrid" rozella, genetically disparate group known mostly environmental dna sequences siste