mpted invasion. u. maydis respond oxidative burst oxidative stress response, regulated gene yap1. response protects u. maydis host defense, necessary pathogen’s virulence.[183] furthermore, u. maydis well-established recombinational dna repair system acts mitosis meiosis.[184] system may assist pathogen surviving dna damage arising host plant’s oxidative defensive response infection.[185] cryptococcus neoformans encapsulated yeast live plants animals. c. neoformans usually infects lungs, phagocytosed alveolar macrophages.[186] some c. neoformans survive inside macrophages, appears basis latency, disseminated disease, resistance antifungal agents. one mechanism c. neoformans survives hostile macrophage environment up-regulating expression genes involved oxidative stress response.[186] another mechanism involves meiosis. majority c. neoformans mating "type a". filaments mating "type a" ordinarily haploid nuclei, become diploid (perhaps endoduplication stimulated nuclear fusion) form blastospores. diploid nuclei blastospores undergo meiosis, including recombination, form haploid basidiospores dispersed.[187] process referred monokaryotic fruiting. process requires gene called dmc1, conserved homologue genes reca bacteria rad51 eukaryotes, mediates homologous chromosome pairing meiosis repair dna double-strand breaks. thus, c. neoformans undergo meiosis, monokaryotic fruiting, promotes recombinational repair oxidative, dna damaging environment host macrophage, repair capability may contribute virulence.[185][187] human use saccharomyces cerevisiae cells shown dic microscopy human use fungi food preparation preservation other purposes extensive long history. mushroom farming mushroom gathering large industries many countries. study historical uses sociological impact fungi known ethnomycology. capacity group produce enormous range natural products antimicrobial other biological activities, many species long used developed industrial production antibiotics, vitamins, anti